  <scaffolding>
    <layer level="1" name="Layer 1">
      <focus/>
      <content>Core definitions: Cryptographic keys, PKI overview, digital certificates, revocation purpose (invalidation before expiration due to compromise, supersedure, etc.). Big picture: Role in key lifecycle (generation, distribution, use, revocation, destruction) for Asset Security in cybersecurity.</content>
    </layer>
    <layer level="2" name="Layer 2">
      <focus/>
      <content>CRL (signed list of revoked cert serial numbers, revocation reasons per RFC 5280: key compromise, CA compromise, etc.; distribution points). OCSP (real-time query protocol for single cert status). PKI roles (CA issues CRLs, OCSP responders). Cert path validation basics (chain building, validity checks).</content>
    </layer>
    <layer level="3" name="Layer 3">
      <focus/>
      <content>Step-by-step revocation: 1) Detect issue (compromise); 2) CA/RA verifies; 3) Add to CRL or OCSP DB with reason/date; 4) Publish CRL periodically or respond via OCSP; 5) Relying parties check status. Best practices: Delta CRLs for efficiency, OCSP stapling for privacy. Hands-on: Simulate CRL issuance.</content>
    </layer>
    <layer level="4" name="Layer 4">
      <focus/>
      <content>Full RFC 5280 cert path validation (build chain to trust anchor, check signatures/validity dates/revocation via CRL/OCSP). Link to incident response (notify, quarantine), cross-domain with Data Security Controls. Real-world: Mitigate risks in enterprise PKI, e.g., Heartbleed bug revocations.</content>
    </layer>
  </scaffolding>
